http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between cotyledons that function as leaves and can photosynthesise versus ones that function as energy reserve organs.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between seedlings where the cotyledon remains within the seed coat versus emerges from the seed coat at germination.
A plant embryo morphology trait [TO:0000064] which indicates if the cotyledons [PO:0020030] emerge from the seed coat [PO:0009088] at germination [GO:0009845].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between seedlings where the cotyledon remains within the seed coat versus emerges from the seed coat at germination.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between glabrous versus hairy cotyledons.
A plant embryo cotyledon morphology trait [TO:0000775] which is the pilosity [PATO:0000066] of the cotyledons [PO:0020030].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between glabrous versus hairy cotyledons.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between glabrous versus hairy hypocotyls, where the hypocotyl is the embryonic axis to which the cotyledons are attached.
A seedling hypocotyl morphology trait [TO:0000769] which is the pilosity [PATO:0000066] of the hypocotyl [PO:0020100].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between glabrous versus hairy hypocotyls, where the hypocotyl is the embryonic axis to which the cotyledons are attached.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between seedlings where the first leaf is scale-like (cataphyll) versus leaf-like.

A plant embryo true leaf formation stage [PO:0001095] morphology trait which is whether the leaf [PO:0025034] at the first stem node [PO:0020141] above the epicotyl [PO:0020035] in a true leaf or a scale leaf.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between seedlings where the first leaf is scale-like (cataphyll) versus leaf-like.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between seedlings where the leaves at the first node are single versus paired.
A plant embryo true leaf formation stage [PO:0001095] morphology trait which is the leaf count [NCIT:C25463] at the first stem node [PO:0020141] above the epicotyl [PO:0020035].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between seedlings where the leaves at the first node are single versus paired.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between seedlings that germinate above versus below ground.
A plant embryo cotyledon morphology trait [TO:0000775] which is the position [PATO:0000140] of seed germination [GO:0009845] relative to the soil surface.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Binary variable distinguishing between seedlings that germinate above versus below ground.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The 2-dimensional projected (scanned) area of the surface of a leaf or a leaf analogue (leaflet, cladode, phyllode).

A leaf area trait [TO:0000540] which is the 2-D [PATO:0001709] area [PATO:0001323] of the leaf lamina [PO:0020039] and petiole [PO:0020038]. For some species the area of a leaf analogue is reported, possibly a leaflet [PO:0020049], cladode [PO:0025354], or phyllode [PO:0025335].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait includes measurements of leaves and leaf analogues, including leaflets, cladodes, and phyllodes. When a measurement is made on a leaf analogue, the tissue measured should be documented as part of the methods or noted as a `context` or under `measurement_remarks`. Leaflet area can alternatively be mapped to the trait `leaflet_area`. It is most common for leaf area measurements to include the petiole; the measurement methods should indicate if the petiole is included in or excluded from the leaf area measurements. For terete leaves, leaf area should still be recorded as the 2-dimensional projected area.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Leaf size SLA, leaf mass & LDMC [LEDA:2.1] (https://uol.de/en/landeco/research/leda/standards)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The 2-dimensional projected (scanned) area of the surface of a leaf or a leaf analogue (leaflet, cladode, phyllode).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Leaf area (in case of compound leaves: leaf, undefined if petiole in- or excluded) [TRY:3112] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The 2-dimensional projected (scanned) area of the surface of the lamina of a single leaflet.
A leaf area trait [TO:0000540] which is the 2-D [PATO:0001709] area [PATO:0001323] of a single leaflet [PO:0020049] lamina [PO:0025060]. This measurement will not include the petiole [PO:0020038].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The 2-dimensional projected (scanned) area of the surface of the lamina of a single leaflet.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Length of a leaf or a leaf analogue, from the leaf apex to the leaf axil (base), including the petiole.
Length [PATO:0000122] of the leaf [PO:0025034] (including the petiole [PO:0020038]), from the leaf apex [PO:0020137] to the leaf axil [PO:0009023] (leaf base [PO:0020040]).

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: If a leaf analogue (leaflet, cladode, or phyllode) is measured instead of a true leaf, this should be noted as a `context` or under `measurement_remarks`.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: maximum leaf length; minimum leaf length [BIEN] (https://bien.nceas.ucsb.edu/bien/biendata)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Length of a leaf or a leaf analogue, from the leaf apex to the leaf axil (base), including the petiole.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Maximum width axis of a leaf or a leaf analogue (a leaflet, cladode, or phyllode), measured perpendicular to the leaf length.
The maximum [NCIT:C25564] width [PATO:0000921] axis of a leaf [PO:0025034] measured perpendicular to [PATO:0002434] the leaf length [PATO:0000122].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait refers to the single line marking the maximum width of the leaf lamina. For a compound leaf the correct measure is the maximum width of the total leaf blade. It is the width measure that will be reported in taxonomic treatments. It is not the `effective_leaf_width`, a trait that records the diameter of the largest circle that can be drawn within the leaf lamina. If a leaf analogue (leaflet, cladode, or phyllode) is measured instead of a true leaf, this should be noted as a `context` or under `measurement_remarks`.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: maximum leaf width; minimum leaf width [BIEN] (https://bien.nceas.ucsb.edu/bien/biendata)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Maximum width axis of a leaf or a leaf analogue (a leaflet, cladode, or phyllode), measured perpendicular to the leaf length.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Thickness of the leaf lamina, generally measured away from the midrib.
The thickness [PATO:0000915] of the leaf lamina [PO:0020039], measured away from the midrib [PO:0020139].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Leaf thickness measurements submitted from the ecological literature will generally avoid the midrib, but not avoid lower order leaf veins. In contrast, leaf thickness measurements from the taxonomic literature will usually include any veins or midribs, because in this literature leaf thickness is generally measured on succulent plants. The `methods` field should document whether the midrib was explicitly included, excluded, or ignored.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Thickness of the leaf lamina, generally measured away from the midrib.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The oven dry mass of a leaf or leaf analogue (leaflet, cladode, phyllode).
A leaf mass trait [TO:0000505] which is the dry [PATO:0001824] mass [PATO:0000125] of a leaf [PO:0025034] or leaf analogue (a leaflet [PO:0020049], cladode [PO:0025354], or phyllode [PO:0025335]).

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait includes measurements of leaves and leaf analogues, including leaflets, cladodes, and phyllodes. When a measurement is made on a leaf analogue, the tissue measured should be documented as part of the methods or noted as a `context` or under `measurement_remarks`. Leaflet dry mass can alternatively be mapped to the trait `leaflet_dry_mass`. It is most common for leaf dry mass measurements to include the petiole; the measurement methods should indicate if the petiole is included in or excluded from the leaf dry mass measurements.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Leaf size SLA, leaf mass & LDMC [LEDA:2.1] (https://uol.de/en/landeco/research/leda/standards)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The oven dry mass of a leaf or leaf analogue (leaflet, cladode, phyllode).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The oven dry mass of a single leaflet.
A leaf dry mass trait [TO:0001014] which is the dry mass of a single leaflet [PO:0020049]. This measurement will not include the petiole [PO:0020038].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The oven dry mass of a single leaflet.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The fresh mass of a leaf or leaf analogue (leaflet, cladode, phyllode).

A leaf mass trait [TO:0000505] which is the mass [PATO:0000125] of a fresh [EnvThes:21976] leaf [PO:0025034], indicating its mass at the time it is picked. For some species the mass of a leaf analogue is reported, possibly a leaflet [PO:0020049], cladode [PO:0025354], or phyllode [PO:0025335].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait includes measurements of leaves and leaf analogues, including leaflets, cladodes, and phyllodes. When a measurement is made on a leaf analogue, the tissue measured should be documented as part of the methods or noted as a `context` or under `measurement_remarks`. It is most common for leaf fresh mass measurements to include the petiole; the measurement methods should indicate if the petiole is included in or excluded from the leaf fresh mass measurements. A source of variation for this trait will be how leaves are stored and if they are partially rehydrated before weighing; these details should be documented in the methods.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The fresh mass of a leaf or leaf analogue (leaflet, cladode, phyllode).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Length of the petiole from the leaf base to the leaf axil.
Length [PATO:0000122] of the petiole [PO:0020038]), from the leaf base [PO:0020040] to the leaf axil [PO:0009023].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Length of the petiole from the leaf base to the leaf axil.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Width of the petiole.
Width [PATO:0000921] of the petiole [PO:0020038].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Width of the petiole.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of leaf dry mass to leaf area, measured on an entire leaf including the petiole; LMA. (The inverse of specific leaf area, SLA.)

A leaf morphology trait [TO:0000748] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of the leaf dry [PATO:0001824] mass [PATO:0000125] to the leaf [PO:0025034] area [PATO:0001323], measured on an entire leaf, including the entire leaf lamina [PO:0020039] and the petiole [PO:0020038].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Leaf mass per area includes measurements submitted as `specific_leaf_area` (SLA); they are simply inverted. Leaf mass per area is explicitly measured on an entire leaf, including the petiole. Measurements made on a piece of the leaf lamina, excluding petiole and midrib, are a separate trait `leaf_lamina_mass_per_area`. If measurements are made on the entire leaf lamina, but the petiole is excluded, this should be noted in the methods or under `measurement_remarks`.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Leaf size SLA, leaf mass & LDMC [LEDA:2.1] (https://uol.de/en/landeco/research/leda/standards)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of leaf dry mass to leaf area, measured on an entire leaf including the petiole; LMA. (The inverse of specific leaf area, SLA.)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: leaf area per leaf dry mass [BIEN] (https://bien.nceas.ucsb.edu/bien/biendata)

Leaf area per leaf dry mass (specific leaf area, SLA or 1/LMA): undefined if petiole is in- or exclu [TRY:3117]; Leaf area per leaf dry mass (specific leaf area, SLA or 1/LMA): petiole included [TRY:3116] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of leaf dry mass to leaf area, measured on a piece of the leaf lamina that does not include the petiole or major veins.

A leaf morphology trait [TO:0000748] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of the leaf dry [PATO:0001824] mass [PATO:0000125] to leaf [PO:0025034] area [PATO:0001323], measured on a piece of the leaf lamina [PO:0020039] located away from major leaf lamina veins [PO:0020138].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait only includes data made on subsamples of a leaf, usually a leaf punch sample associated with leaf strength measurements or from the herbivory literature. For whole-leaf LMA/SLA data, see the trait `leaf_mass_per_area`

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Leaf area per leaf dry mass (specific leaf area, SLA or 1/LMA): petiole excluded [TRY:3115] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of leaf dry mass to leaf area, measured on a piece of the leaf lamina that does not include the petiole or major veins.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Leaf area per leaf dry mass (specific leaf area, SLA or 1/LMA) petiole, rhachis and midrib excluded [TRY:3086] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)
http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#rela: Leaf size SLA, leaf mass & LDMC [LEDA:2.1] (https://uol.de/en/landeco/research/leda/standards)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of leaf dry mass to leaf fresh volume.
The ratio [PATO:0001470] of leaf [PO:0025034] dry [PATO:0001824] mass [PATO:0000125] to leaf fresh [EnvThes:21976] volume [PATO:0000918].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of leaf dry mass to leaf fresh volume.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Leaf density (leaf tissue density, leaf dry mass per leaf volume) [TRY:48] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of total plant leaf area to total plant dry mass; LAR.
A leaf area trait [TO:0000540] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of a plant's [PO:0000003] total [NCIT:C25304] leaf [PO:0025034] area [PATO:0001323] to total plant dry mass [TO_0000352].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Since the total plant dry mass is required for leaf area ratio measurements, this is standardly measured only on young plants or plants grown for experiments where the entire plant can be harvested. It is best practice for leaf area measurements to include the petiole.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of total plant leaf area to total plant dry mass; LAR.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Leaf area per plant dry mass (leaf area ratio; LAR) [TRY:109] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of leaf dry mass to total plant dry mass.
A leaf mass trait [TO:0000505] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of a plant's total leaf dry mass [APD:glossary/40080] to total plant dry mass [TO:0000352].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of leaf dry mass to total plant dry mass.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Plant biomass and allometry: Leaf dry mass per plant dry mass (leaf weight ratio, LWR) [TRY:110] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of leaf dry mass to leaf fresh mass; LDMC.
A leaf mass trait [TO:0000505] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of leaf dry mass [TO:0001014] to leaf [PO:0025034] fresh mass [APD:glossary/40044].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Two similar traits are `leaf_water_content_per_dry_mass`, the ratio of leaf water content to leaf dry mass and `leaf_water_content_per_fresh_mass`, the ratio of leaf water content to leaf fresh mass.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of leaf dry mass to leaf fresh mass; LDMC.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: leaf dry mass per leaf fresh mass [BIEN] (https://bien.nceas.ucsb.edu/bien/biendata)
Leaf dry mass per leaf fresh mass (leaf dry matter content, LDMC) [TRY:47] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of leaf fresh mass to leaf area, measured on an entire leaf including the petiole.

A leaf area trait [TO:0000540] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of the leaf [PO:0025034] fresh mass [APD:glossary/40044]. to the leaf area [PATO:0001323], measured on an entire leaf, including the entire leaf lamina [PO:0020039] and the petiole [PO:0020038].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Leaf fresh mass per area is explicitly measured on an entire leaf, including the petiole.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: Leaf fresh mass per leaf area

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of leaf fresh mass to leaf area, measured on an entire leaf including the petiole.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Leaf area per leaf fresh mass (specific leaf area (SLA or 1/LMA) based on leaf fresh mass) [TRY:125] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#pref.@value: Leaf fresh mass per leaf area

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of the mass of water in a fresh leaf (leaf water content) to leaf surface area; leaf succulence.
A leaf mass trait [TO:0000505] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of the mass [PATO:0000125] of water [CHEBI:15377] in a fresh [EnvThes:21976] leaf [PO:0025034] to leaf area [PATO:0001323].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: Leaf water content per unit leaf area (leaf succulence)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of the mass of water in a fresh leaf (leaf water content) to leaf surface area; leaf succulence.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#pref.@value: Leaf water content per unit leaf area (leaf succulence)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of the mass of water in a fresh leaf (leaf water content) to leaf dry mass.
A leaf mass trait [TO:0000505] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of the mass [PATO:0000125] of water [CHEBI:15377] in a fresh [EnvThes:21976] leaf [PO:0025034] to leaf dry mass [TO:0001014].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: A similar trait that is recorded by a greater number of studies is `leaf_dry_matter_content`, the ratio of a leaf dry mass to leaf fresh mass.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: Leaf water content per unit leaf dry mass

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of the mass of water in a fresh leaf (leaf water content) to leaf dry mass.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Leaf water content per leaf dry mass (not saturated) [TRY:14] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#pref.@value: Leaf water content per unit leaf dry mass

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of the mass of water in a fresh leaf (leaf water content) to leaf fresh mass

A leaf mass trait [TO:0000505] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of the mass [PATO:0000125] of water [CHEBI:15377] in a fresh [EnvThes:21976] leaf [PO:0025034] to leaf fresh mass [APD:glossary/40044].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: A similar trait that is recorded by a greater number of studies is `leaf_dry_matter_content`, the ratio of a leaf dry mass to leaf fresh mass.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: Leaf water content per unit leaf fresh mass

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of the mass of water in a fresh leaf (leaf water content) to leaf fresh mass

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#pref.@value: Leaf water content per unit leaf fresh mass

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of the mass of water in a leaf (leaf water content) to the mass of a saturated leaf. A saturated leaf is one that has been hydrated to its maximal water holding capacity and is at full turgor.

A leaf mass trait [TO:0000505] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of the mass [PATO:0000125] of water [CHEBI:15377] in a saturated leaf [PO:0025034] to the mass of a saturated leaf. A saturated leaf is one that has been hydrated to its maximum [NCIT:C25564] water holding capacity [IOBC:200906064703668091], known as full turgor [PATO:0001620].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: Leaf water content per unit saturated leaf mass

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Leaf water content per leaf dry mass (at saturation) [TRY:3122] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of the mass of water in a leaf (leaf water content) to the mass of a saturated leaf. A saturated leaf is one that has been hydrated to its maximal water holding capacity and is at full turgor.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#pref.@value: Leaf water content per unit saturated leaf mass

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of leaf cell wall dry mass to leaf dry mass. This is the fraction of cell wall material that can be recovered from total leaf biomass.
A leaf mass trait [TO:0000505] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of cell wall [GO:0009505] dry mass to leaf dry mass [TO:0001014].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of leaf cell wall dry mass to leaf dry mass. This is the fraction of cell wall material that can be recovered from total leaf biomass.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Leaf cell wall mass per leaf dry mass [TRY:3375] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Variable distinguishing between general leaf form (shape) categories.
A leaf shape trait [TO:0000492] which is inclusive [NCIT:C166400] categories describing the shape [PATO:0000052] of a leaf [PO:0025034] as broad, needle-like, or scale-like.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Terms identifying the plant organ responsible for photosynthesis are mapped to the trait `plant_photosynthetic_organ`, while `leaf_form_general` only includes terms pertaining to the general form of the leaf. The trait `leaf_shape` provides detailed vocabulary to describe a leaf's shape.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Variable distinguishing between general leaf form (shape) categories.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: leaf_form_1 [GIFT:4.11.1] (https://gift.uni-goettingen.de)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Shapes of a leaf or leaflet.

A leaf shape trait [TO:0000492] which is the shape [PATO:0000052] and form of a leaf [PO:0025034], considering the ratio [PATO:0001470] of leaf length [PATO:0000122] to leaf width [PATO:0000921], the position [PATO:0000140] of the maximum [NCIT:C25564] width dimension relative to the length axis [NCIT:C25154], and the curvature [PATO:0001591] of the leaf margin [PO:0020128].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait includes terms to describe the shape of leaves, regardless of if they are broad leaves, scale-like leaves, or needle-like leaves. For compound leaves, it is generally the shape of the leaflet that is recorded. See the trait `leaf_type` for broad terms referencing leaf form (broadleaf, needle, scale) and `plant_photosynthetic_organ` for terms indicating which plant organ or tissue functions as the plant's primary photosynthetic organ (e.g. phyllode, cladode, article).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Shapes of a leaf or leaflet.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The shape of the basal margin of a leaf.

A leaf shape trait [TO:0000492] which is the variation in shapes and forms of a leaf base [PO:0020040], especially considering the curvature [PATO:0001591] of the leaf margin [PO:0020128] near where it attaches to the petiole [PO:0020038].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The shape of the basal margin of a leaf.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Shape of the leaf margin, referencing incisions or projections in the outermost 1/8 of the leaf lamina.

A leaf shape trait [TO:0000492] which is the edge shape [PATO:0002267] of the leaf margin [PO:0020128], in particular the presence or absence of leaf lamina teeth [PO:0025518] and the shape [PATO:0000052] of the leaf lamina teeth (serrate, dentate, or crenate).

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Terms describing leaf lamina projections and incisions that are greater than 1/8 of the distance to the midrib are captured under the traits `leaf_lobation` and `leaf_division_detailed`.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Shape of the leaf margin, referencing incisions or projections in the outermost 1/8 of the leaf lamina.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The posture (curvature or curling) of the leaf margin.

A leaf shape trait [TO:0000492] which is the degree of curvature [PATO:0001591] or curling [PATO:0000405] of the leaf margin [PO:0020128] along the side of the leaf, at the leaf apex [PO:0020137], and at the leaf base [PO:0020040].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait captures the posture of the leaf margin, where posture refers to the placement of different parts of the leaf's margin relative to a flat plane. This trait's definition and allowable levels will be further refined once more data are available to map onto possible trait values.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The posture (curvature or curling) of the leaf margin.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: A trait that indicates whether a leaf lamina or leaflets display any divisions or dissections on a 2-dimensional plane that extend greater than 1/8 of the distance to the midrib.
A leaf shape trait [TO:0000492] which is the presence or absence of leaf lamina lobes [PO:0025517] along the leaf margin [PO:0020128] and how far the lobes extend toward the midrib [PO:0020139].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: For terms pertaining to 2-dimensional leaf lamina divisions and incisions that are less than 1/8 of the distance to the midrib, see the trait `leaf_margin`. See also the trait `leaf_division` for more detailed leaf lobation (and leaf compoundness) trait values. Note that there might be some species that grade from deeply lobed simple leaves to compound leaves.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A trait that indicates whether a leaf lamina or leaflets display any divisions or dissections on a 2-dimensional plane that extend greater than 1/8 of the distance to the midrib.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: A binary trait that indicates whether a leaf lamina is simple or divided into discontinuous leaflets (compound).
A leaf shape trait [TO:0000492] which is whether a leaf [PO:0025034] is a simple leaf [PO:0020042] or is divided into leaflets [PO:0020049] making it a compound leaf [PO:0020043].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: See also the trait <U+00E2><U+20AC><U+02DC>leaf_division' for more detailed leaf compoundness trait values. Note that there might be some species that grade from deeply lobed simple leaves (see trait `leaf_lobation`)  to compound leaves.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A binary trait that indicates whether a leaf lamina is simple or divided into discontinuous leaflets (compound).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: A trait that captures the types of lobed leaves and compound leaves, including the arrangement of the lobes or leaflets relative to the midrib or other primary veins and the number of orders of axes across which there are incisions or divisions.

A leaf shape trait [TO:0000492] which indicates types [NCIT:C25284] of lobed leaves [PO:0025517] and compound leaves [PO:0020043], including the arrangement [NCIT:C61532] of the lobes or leaflets [PO:0020049] with respect to the midrib [PO:0020139] or other primary leaf veins [PO:0025413] and the number of orders of axes [NCIT:C25154] across which there are incisions or divisions.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait provides detailed description of leaf divisions, beyond what is captured in `leaf_compoundness` (simple versus compound) and `leaf_lobation` (entire versus lobed). The term 'divided' is meant to indicate lobing, such as 'trichotomously divided', but as 'divided' is also used in some context to indicate the divisions of leaves into leaflets, it is avoided as a trait value for this trait.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A trait that captures the types of lobed leaves and compound leaves, including the arrangement of the lobes or leaflets relative to the midrib or other primary veins and the number of orders of axes across which there are incisions or divisions.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The maximum perpendicular height of a leaf when positioned on a flat surface.

A leaf shape trait [TO:0000492] which is the maximum [NCIT:C25564] perpendicular [PATO:0002434] height [PATO:0000119] of a leaf [PO:0025034] placed on a flat surface, indicating the 3-D extent [PATO:0001710] of the leaf. This generally corresponds with whether the leaf is curled [FLOPO:0010468].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: A measure of how planar versus 3-dimensional a leaf is. The term posture refers to the placement of different parts of the leaf's lamina relative to a flat plane.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The maximum perpendicular height of a leaf when positioned on a flat surface.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The 3-dimension shape of the surface of the leaf lamina, including its degree of curvature and bending.

A leaf shape trait [TO:0000492] which is the 3-D shape [PATO:0002266] of the surface [NCIT:C25245] of the leaf lamina [PO:0020039], including its degree of curvature [PATO:0001591] and whether it is bent [PATO:0000617].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The 3-dimension shape of the surface of the leaf lamina, including its degree of curvature and bending.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Variable describing whether mature adult phase leaves have a glaucous appearance, the colour due to being covered with a smooth, usually whitish to bluish epicuticular wax that can easily be rubbed off.

A leaf morphology trait [TO:0000748] which is the presence or absence of epicuticular wax [PO:0025388] on the leaf lamina [PO:0020039] of a fully expanded adult phase leaf [PO:0006340], giving the leaf lamina surface a white-coloured [PATO:0000014] or blue-coloured waxy [PATO:0002384] appearance, termed glaucous.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: The accompanying methods should specify if the trait was scored on the upper (adaxial) or lower (abaxial) surface of the leaf; in the absence of any notes, it is assumed the trait was scored on the upper (adaxial) leaf surface.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Variable describing whether mature adult phase leaves have a glaucous appearance, the colour due to being covered with a smooth, usually whitish to bluish epicuticular wax that can easily be rubbed off.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Variable describing whether mature (fully expanded) adult phase leaves on adult plants have hairs (trichomes).
A leaf pubescence trait [TO:0002722] which is the presence or absence of trichomes [PO:0006504] (hairs) on the leaf lamina [PO:0020039] of a fully expanded adult phase leaf [PO:0006340].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait captures the presence or absence of hairs on mature (fully expanded), adult phase leaves on adult plants. Best practice is to sample leaves that are recently fully expanded, since older leaves have often shed many of their hairs. The accompanying methods should specify if the trait was scored on the upper (adaxial) or lower (abaxial) surface of the leaf; in the absence of any notes, it is assumed the trait was scored on the upper (adaxial) leaf surface.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Leaf emergences (pubescence, pruinescence, hairs, spines, thorns) [TRY:677] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Variable describing whether mature (fully expanded) adult phase leaves on adult plants have hairs (trichomes).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Variable describing whether fully expanded juvenile phase leaves (on adult or juvenile plants) have hairs (trichomes).

A leaf pubescence trait [TO:0002722] which is the presence or absence of trichomes [PO:0006504] (hairs) on the leaf lamina [PO:0020039] of a juvenile vascular leaf [PO:0006339] (on adult or juvenile plants).

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait captures the presence or absence of hairs on fully-expanded juvenile phase leaves. It is best practice for the methods to specify whether these leaves were sampled from adult or juvenile plants. The accompanying methods should also specify if the trait was scored on the upper (adaxial) or lower (abaxial) surface of the leaf; in the absence of any notes, it is assumed the trait was scored on the upper (adaxial) leaf surface.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Leaf emergences (pubescence, pruinescence, hairs, spines, thorns) [TRY:677] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Variable describing whether fully expanded juvenile phase leaves (on adult or juvenile plants) have hairs (trichomes).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Variable describing whether immature (still expanding) adult phase leaves on adult plants have hairs (trichomes).

A leaf pubescence trait [TO:0002722] which is the presence or absence of trichomes [PO:0006504] (hairs) on the leaf lamina [PO:0020039] of an adult phase leaf [PO:0006340] still in the vascular leaf expansion stage [PO:0001052].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait captures the presence or absence of hairs on immature (still expanding) leaves on adult plants. The accompanying methods should specify if the trait was scored on the upper (adaxial) or lower (abaxial) surface of the leaf; in the absence of any notes, it is assumed the trait was scored on the upper (adaxial) leaf surface.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Leaf emergences (pubescence, pruinescence, hairs, spines, thorns) [TRY:677] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Variable describing whether immature (still expanding) adult phase leaves on adult plants have hairs (trichomes).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Leaf arrangement at a stem node, indicating the relative number and position of leaves at a single stem note.

A leaf [PO:0025034] spatial pattern [PATO:0000060] trait which is the phyllotaxy [TO:0006014] of leaves, indicating a leaf's position [TO:0000541] relative to other leaves at a stem node [PO:0020141].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait only includes true phyllotaxis, the arrangement of leaves at a single node, while the trait `leaf arrangement` indicates how the leaves are presented along the entire shoot system. See the trait `stem_growth_habit` for whole-plant leaf pattern terms, such as `rosette`.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Leaf distribution along the shoot axis (arrangement type) [TRY:16] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Leaf arrangement at a stem node, indicating the relative number and position of leaves at a single stem note.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Leaf arrangement across stem nodes, indicating the 3-dimensional arrangement of leaves along the length of the stem.

A leaf [PO:0025034] spatial pattern [PATO:0000060] trait which is the position [TO:0000541] and arrangement [NCIT:C61532] of leaves between stem nodes [PO:0020141], indicating how leaves align and cluster along the vegetative shoot system [PO:0025607].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Leaf arrangement, as defined for this trait, indicates patterns of leaf arrangement across nodes, including both formal terms (decussate, distichous, spiral) as well as indications of leaf clustering due to variation in internode length. See the trait `leaf phyllotaxis` for terms describing leaf arrangement at a single node. See the trait `stem_growth_habit` for whole-plant leaf pattern terms, such as `rosette`.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Leaf distribution along the shoot axis (arrangement type) [TRY:16] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Leaf arrangement across stem nodes, indicating the 3-dimensional arrangement of leaves along the length of the stem.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The angle between a shoot and a leaf that connects to the shoot axis.
A leaf position trait [TO:0000541] which is the angle [PATO:0002326] of a leaf axil [PO:0009023], the space between a leaf [PO:0025034] and the stem [PO:0009047] to which it is attached.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait records the angle between the upper surface of a leaf and the stem to which it is attached. The slope of the leaf lamina relative to the solar zenith is a separate trait, `leaf_inclination_angle`.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The angle between a shoot and a leaf that connects to the shoot axis.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The inclination angle of the upper (adaxial) leaf lamina surface relative to a horizontal plane, such that a leaf surface facing the solar zenith has an angle of 0.

A leaf position trait [TO:0000541] which is the inclination angle [PATO:0002326] of the adaxial [PATO:0002047] leaf lamina [PO:0020039] surface relative to a horizontal [PATO:0001855] plane, such that an adaxial leaf surface facing the solar zenith [ECSO:00002723] has an angle of 0.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait records the slope of the leaf lamina relative to the ground surface. The angle between a stem and the leaf lamina is a separate trait, `leaf_axil_angle`. Complanate leaves can be scored as having a `leaf_inclination_angle` of 0.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The inclination angle of the upper (adaxial) leaf lamina surface relative to a horizontal plane, such that a leaf surface facing the solar zenith has an angle of 0.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Leaf angle (inclition, orientation) [TRY:3] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Binary variable describing whether leaves are pendulous, hanging loosely downward and possessing the ability to flutter.
A leaf position trait [TO:0000541] which indicates whether leaves [PO:0025034] are pendulous [APD:glossary/40066], hanging loosely downward and possessing the ability to flutter.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This is a binary categorical trait, scoring whether leaves are pendulous and therefore hanging loosely downward and able to flutter. Two additional traits, `leaf_inclination_angle` and `leaf_axil_angle` document the actual angle of the leaf lamina relative to, respectively, the solar zenith and the stem.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Binary variable describing whether leaves are pendulous, hanging loosely downward and possessing the ability to flutter.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Cross-sectional area of a stem, including both wood and bark.
A stem morphology trait [TO:0000361] which is the cross-sectional [NCIT:C63795] area [PATO:0001323] of a stem [PO:0009047] segment which includes the bark [PO:0004518].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This is not a trait itself, since it is dependent on the location sampled. However, values might be reported that are effectively contexts for another trait, such as bark thickness or Huber value.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Cross-sectional area of a stem, including both wood and bark.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Cross-sectional area of a stem without bark.

A stem morphology trait [TO:0000361] which is the cross-sectional [NCIT:C63795] area [PATO:0001323] of a stem [PO:0009047] segment from which the bark [PO:0004518] has been removed; this includes both sapwood [PO:0004513] and, if present heartwood [PO:0004512].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This is not a trait itself, since it is dependent on the location sampled. However, values might be reported that are effectively contexts for another trait, such as bark thickness or Huber value. Although it is defined as the diameter of the entire stem without bark, it is generally measured on narrow branches that have not yet developed heartwood and therefore is the cross-section of sapwood.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of stem dry mass to stem fresh volume, measured on an herbaceous stem segment.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of two times a single bark thickness measure to stem diameter, to adjust for increasing bark thickness with increasing stem diameter.
A bark morphology trait which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of two times bark [PO:0004518] thickness [PATO:0000915] to the stem [PO:0009047] diameter [PATO:0001334].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of two times a single bark thickness measure to stem diameter, to adjust for increasing bark thickness with increasing stem diameter.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of bark dry mass to bark fresh volume.
The ratio [PATO:0001470] of bark [PO:0004518] dry [PATO:0001824] mass [PATO:0000125] to the corresponding fresh [EnvThes:21976] bark volume [PATO:0000918].

The ratio [PATO:0001470] of the mass [PATO:0000125] of water [CHEBI:15377] in bark [PO:0004518] (bark water content [APD:glossary/40014]) to bark dry [PATO:0001824] mass.

A bark mass trait [TO:0000952] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of the mass [PATO:0000125] of water [CHEBI:15377] in bark [PO:0004518] to the fresh mass [APD:glossary/40044] of bark that is at maximum [NCIT:C25564] water holding capacity [IOBC:200906064703668091], known as full turgor [PATO:0001620].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: Bark water content per unit saturated bark mass

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#pref.@value: Bark water content per unit saturated bark mass

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Maximum root diameter.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Maximum root diameter.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Categorical root system descriptions that indicate the branchiness and texture of the root system and the depth of the root system.

A root system morphology trait [TO:0000985] which are categorical [STATO:0000252] trait values that capture the branchiness [PATO:0002009] and texture [PATO:0000150] of the root system [PO:0025025] and the root system depth [TO:0001058].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: The trait values listed are those specified in the root system classification scheme proposed by Cannon in 1949.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Categorical root system descriptions that indicate the branchiness and texture of the root system and the depth of the root system.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of the volume of fine roots (<0.5mm diameter) to the volume of coarse roots (>0.5mm diameter).

A root system morphology trait [TO:0000985] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of the volume [PATO:0000918] of fine roots [EnvThes:20581] (those <0.5mm in diameter) to the volume of coarse roots [APD:glossary/40026] (those >0.5 mm in diameter).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Root biomass depth distribution coefficient ('B' from Gale & Grigal 1987), where high values indicate that root biomass is allocated deeper in the soil. To calculate the model parameter, the required input is a plot of the cumulative root distribution from the surface, where [Y] is the cumulative fraction of roots from the surface to a depth [d]. An asymptotic nonlinear model is used to describe the vertical root distribution: Y = 1 - b^d where Y is the cumulative root fraction from the surface to soil depth d in centimeters and b the estimated parameter.

A root system morphology trait [TO:0000985] which is a model parameter [STATO:0000034] indicating the distribution [PATO:0000060] of a plant's roots [PO:0009005] with depth [PATO:0001595]. To calculate the model parameter, the required input is a plot of the cumulative root distribution from the surface, where [Y] is the cumulative fraction of roots from the surface to a depth [d]. An asymptotic nonlinear model is used to describe the vertical root distribution: Y = 1 - b^d where Y is the cumulative root fraction from the surface to soil depth d in centimeters and b the estimated parameter.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Root evenness of dry mass vertical distribution [TRY:3033] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Root biomass depth distribution coefficient ('B' from Gale & Grigal 1987), where high values indicate that root biomass is allocated deeper in the soil. To calculate the model parameter, the required input is a plot of the cumulative root distribution from the surface, where [Y] is the cumulative fraction of roots from the surface to a depth [d]. An asymptotic nonlinear model is used to describe the vertical root distribution: Y = 1 - b^d where Y is the cumulative root fraction from the surface to soil depth d in centimeters and b the estimated parameter.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Variable describing whether a plant has a tap root.

A root system morphology trait [TO:0000985] which indicates if the root system [PO:0025025] is one where the primary root [PO:0020127] remains the dominant root, developing into a taproot, a long [PATO:0000573], thick [PATO:0000591] root with few branches, or whether the lateral roots [PO:0020121] are of similar length to the primary root.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Variable describing whether a plant has a tap root.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of root length to root dry mass; SRL.
A root morphology trait [TO:0000043] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of root [PO:0009005] length [PATO:0000122] to root dry mass [TO:0000078].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of root length to root dry mass; SRL.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Root length per root dry mass (specific root length, SRL) [TRY:1080] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of taproot length (primary root length) to taproot dry mass; STRL.
A root morphology trait [TO:0000043] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of primary root [PO:0020127] length [PATO:0000122] to primary root dry mass [TO:0000078]

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait is usually measured during the very early stage of growth, capturing how efficiently seedlings reach reliable water.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Coarse root length per coarse root dry mass (specific coarse root length, SRL) [TRY:1550] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of taproot length (primary root length) to taproot dry mass; STRL.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of root surface area to root dry mass; specific root area.
A root morphology trait [TO:0000043] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of root [PO:0009005] surface area [EnvThes:21564] to root dry mass [TO:0000078].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: Root surface area per unit root dry mass (specific root area)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of root surface area to root dry mass; specific root area.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Root surface area per root dry mass (specific root area) [TRY:1089] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#pref.@value: Root surface area per unit root dry mass (specific root area)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of woody root dry mass to woody root fresh volume.

A root morphology trait [TO:0000043] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of the dry mass [PATO:0000125] of a unit of wood [PO_0005848] from a root [PO:0009005]to its fresh fresh [EnvThes:21976] volume [PATO:0000918].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of woody root dry mass to woody root fresh volume.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Root tissue density (root dry mass per root volume) [TRY:82] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of total root system dry mass to total shoot system dry mass.
A whole plant morphology trait [TO:0000398] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of a plant's root dry mass [TO:0000078] to its shoot dry mass [TO:0000552].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait is usually measured on experimentally grown seedlings where it is possible to collect the entire root system.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of total root system dry mass to total shoot system dry mass.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of root dry mass to root fresh mass; root dry matter content, RDMC.
A root mass trait [TO:0000279] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of root dry mass [TO:0000078] to root [PO:0009005] fresh mass [APD:glossary/40044].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of root dry mass to root fresh mass; root dry matter content, RDMC.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Root dry mass per root fresh mass (root dry matter content; RDMC) [TRY:785] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The ratio of total root system dry mass to whole plant dry mass.
A root mass trait [TO:0000279] which is the ratio [PATO:0001470] of the total root dry mass [TO:0000078] to whole plant [PO:0000003] dry mass [APD:glossary/40080].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The ratio of total root system dry mass to whole plant dry mass.

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exac: Plant biomass and allometry: Root mass fraction (fraction of root dry mass per whole plant dry mass) [TRY:470] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The fraction of total reproductive investment required to mature a seed that is invested in non-seed tissues. It is calculated as one minus, the ratio of total biomass investment in seeds to total biomass investment in all reproductive tissues, including flower buds, flowers, fruits, dispersal tissues, aborted seeds, and successfully matured seeds.

A reproductive shoot system [PO:0025082] biomass allocation [EnvThes:21360] trait which is one minus the ratio [PATO:0001470] of total plant seed [PO:0009010] dry [PATO:0001824] mass [PATO:0000125] to total plant reproductive shoot system tissue dry mass where reproductive tissues include all flower buds [PO:0000056], flowers [PO:0009046], fruits [PO:0009001], dispersal [EnvThes:21038] tissues, and seeds produced during the developmental process involved in reproduction [GO:0003006].

@graph.http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#clos: Plant biomass and allometry: Reproductive dry mass per plant dry mass (reproductive weight fraction) [TRY:1046] (https://www.try-db.org/de/de.php)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The fraction of total reproductive investment required to mature a seed that is invested in non-seed tissues. It is calculated as one minus, the ratio of total biomass investment in seeds to total biomass investment in all reproductive tissues, including flower buds, flowers, fruits, dispersal tissues, aborted seeds, and successfully matured seeds.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The mass of seed accessory costs, which is the total biomass investment in all reproductive tissues, excluding biomass invested in successfully matured seeds; it includes all biomass invested in flower buds, flowers, fruits, dispersal tissues and aborted seeds.

A reproductive shoot system [PO:0025082] biomass allocation [EnvThes:21360] trait which is the sum of the dry [PATO:0001824] mass [PATO:0000125] of all flower buds [PO:0000056], flowers [PO:0009046], fruits [PO:0009001], aborted seeds, and dispersal [EnvThes:21038] tissues produced during the developmental process involved in reproduction [GO:0003006], but excludes mature [PATO:0001701] seed [PO:0009010] dry mass.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The mass of seed accessory costs, which is the total biomass investment in all reproductive tissues, excluding biomass invested in successfully matured seeds; it includes all biomass invested in flower buds, flowers, fruits, dispersal tissues and aborted seeds.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The number of stamens or stamen bundles (fascicles) in one whorl, considering both fertile stamens and staminodes.

An androecium morphology trait [TO:0000994] which is the total count [NCIT:C25463] of stamens [PO:0009029], staminodes [PO:0009077] or stamen bundles (fascicles [NCIT:C79692]) in each floral whorl [PO:0025023].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This character is not applicable for spiral or irregular stamen arrangements, nor when there is a single structural stamen (i.e., one stamen, no staminodes; e.g., Chloranthus, Chloranthaceae). Definition derived from Schoenenberger et al. (2020) for their character '332. Androecium structural merism (C1)'

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: Number of androecium parts in each whorl (Androecium structural merism)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The number of stamens or stamen bundles (fascicles) in one whorl, considering both fertile stamens and staminodes.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#pref.@value: Number of androecium parts in each whorl (Androecium structural merism)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Structural phyllotaxy of the androecium, considering both fertile stamens and staminodes. In cases of stamen fascicles, it is the phyllotaxis of fascicles, not individual stamens that are recorded.

An androecium morphology trait [TO:0000994] which is the spatial pattern or distribution [PATO:0000060] (phyllotaxy [TO:0006014]) of stamen [PO:0009029], staminodes [PO:0009077] or stamen bundles (fascicles [NCIT:C79692]) in each floral whorl [PO:0025023].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This character is not applicable when there is a single structural stamen (i.e., one stamen, no staminodes; e.g., Chloranthus, Chloranthaceae). Definition and trait values derived from Schoenenberger et al. (2020) for their character '330. Androecium structural phyllotaxy (D1)'

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Structural phyllotaxy of the androecium, considering both fertile stamens and staminodes. In cases of stamen fascicles, it is the phyllotaxis of fascicles, not individual stamens that are recorded.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The number of whorls, considering both fertile stamens and staminodes. In cases of stamen fascicles, the count of whorls of fascicles is recorded.

An androecium morphology trait [TO:0000994] which is the total count [NCIT:C25463] of whorls [PO:0025023] comprising the androecium [PO:0009061], considering both stamen [PO:0009029] and staminodes [PO:0009077]. If stamens are grouped into fascicles [NCIT:C79692], the trait is the count of whorls of fascicles.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This character is not applicable for spiral or irregular stamen arrangements, or when there is a single structural stamen (i.e., one stamen, no staminodes; e.g., Chloranthus, Chloranthaceae). Definition derived from Schoenenberger et al. (2020) for their character '331. Number of androecium structural whorls (C1)'

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The number of whorls, considering both fertile stamens and staminodes. In cases of stamen fascicles, the count of whorls of fascicles is recorded.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Anther attachment refers to the area of insertion of the filament on the anther connective (i.e. the tissue connecting the two thecae of an anther).

An androecium morphology trait [TO:0000994] which indicates how the filament [PO:0009067] is attached to [PATO:0001667] the tissue [CARO:0000043] connecting the two thecae [PO:0009069] (pollen [PO:0025281] sacs) of the anthers [PO:0009066], affecting the spatial pattern [PATO:0000060] of the stamens [PO:0009029].

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Definition and trait values derived from Schoenenberger et al. (2020) for their character '312. Anther attachment (D1)'

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Anther attachment refers to the area of insertion of the filament on the anther connective (i.e. the tissue connecting the two thecae of an anther).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Apical (distal) connective extensions (also called 'distal connective protrusions') are sterile anther structures that distally extend beyond the level of the thecae (i.e., the two lateral pairs of pollen sacs of a tetrasporangiate anther).

An androecium morphology trait [TO:0000994] which is whether anthers [PO:0009066] have protrusions [NCIT:C50710] that extend above the two theca [PO:0009069] (pollen [PO:0025281] sacs), and, if present, the shape [PATO:0000052] and the relative length [PATO:0000122] of the protrusion relative to the length of the entire anther.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait records both absence or presence of anther connective extensions and also the shape of these extensions in terms of length in relation to the length of the thecae. Definition and trait values derived from Schoenenberger et al. (2020) for their character '314. Connective extension (apical) (D1)'

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Apical (distal) connective extensions (also called 'distal connective protrusions') are sterile anther structures that distally extend beyond the level of the thecae (i.e., the two lateral pairs of pollen sacs of a tetrasporangiate anther).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Anther dehiscence refers to the type of opening of the anther when releasing its pollen through the stomia.

An androecium morphology trait [TO:0000994] which is the length [PATO:0000122] and shape [PATO:0000052] of the stomia [PO:0020101] that form the anther dehiscence zone [PO:0005011]; stomia are the usually slit-like [PATO:0002482] openings in the anther [PO:0009066] through which pollen [PO:0025281] is released.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Definition and trait values derived from Schoenenberger et al. (2020) for their character '313. Anther dehiscence (D1)'

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Anther dehiscence refers to the type of opening of the anther when releasing its pollen through the stomia.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Orientation of anther at anthesis.

An androecium morphology trait [TO:0000994] which is the position [PATO:0000140] and orientation [PATO:0000133] of the stomia [PO:0020101] that form the anther dehiscence zone [PO:0005011]; stomia are the slit-like [PATO:0002482] openings in the anther [PO:0009066] through which pollen [PO:0025281] is released.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Anthers of angiosperms are rather uniform in their basic structure. They normally have four microsporangia (pollen sacs) that are arranged pair-wise in two thecae. The two microsporangia of a theca usually release their pollen grains through a common opening (stomium). Often, it is difficult to establish anther orientation clearly in a flower as this is a gradual feature with many intermediate stages. Definition and trait values derived from Schoenenberger et al. (2020) for their character '311. Anther orientation (D1)'

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Orientation of anther at anthesis.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The dominant flower colour, where the entire flower, the petals, or the sepals may be responsible for the observed colour.

A floral organ morphology trait [TO:0000862] which is the dominant (primary [NCIT:C25251]) colour [PATO:0000014] of the flower [PO:0009046. The petals [PO:0009032] (corolla [PO:0009059]), sepals [PO:0009031] (calyx [PO:0009060]), or the entire perianth [PO:0009058] may be responsible for the main colour observed.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Most data mapped to `flower_colour` has probably been scored based on perianth colour, but if a dataset does not differentiate between the two traits it is mapped to `flower_colour`.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The dominant flower colour, where the entire flower, the petals, or the sepals may be responsible for the observed colour.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The dominant colour of the perianth parts (sepals, petals and tepals).

A floral organ morphology trait [TO:0000862] which is the dominant (primary [NCIT:C25251]) colour [PATO:0000014] of the perianth [PO:0009058] parts (sepals [PO:0009031], petals [PO:0009032], and tepals [PO:0009033]).

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: This trait refers explicitly to the colour of the petals, sepals and tepals, while the trait 'flower colour' refers to the colour of the entire flower. See also data under `flower_colour`.  Most data mapped to `flower_colour` has probably been scored based on perianth colour, but if a dataset does not differentiate between the two traits it is mapped to `flower_colour`.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The dominant colour of the perianth parts (sepals, petals and tepals).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The length of the flower.

A floral organ morphology trait [TO:0000862] which is the length [PATO:0000122] of the flower [PO:0009046] from the base of the receptable [PO:0009064] or the base of an inferior ovary [PO:0009072] to the tip of the flower, measured at anthesis [PO:0009068]. It excludes the length of the pedicel [PO:0030112].

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The maximum diameter of the flower at anthesis, considering all floral organs, but most commonly the diameter from petal  tip to petal tip.

A floral organ morphology trait [TO:0000862] which is the maximum diameter [PATO:0001334] of the flower [PO:0009046] at anthesis [PO:0009068], considering all floral organs, but most commonly the diameter from petal  [PO:0009032] tip to petal tip.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The maximum diameter of the flower at anthesis, considering all floral organs, but most commonly the diameter from petal  tip to petal tip.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: The position and orientation of the flower.
A floral organ morphology trait [TO:0000862] which is the position [PATO:0000140] and orientation [PATO:0000133] of the flower [PO:0009046].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The position and orientation of the flower.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Maximum flower number produced.
A floral organ morphology trait [TO:0000862] which is the maximum [NCIT:C25564] count [NCIT:C25463] of flowers [PO:0009046] on an individual [EFO:0000542].

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Maximum flower number produced.
